onseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic tissue","Cardiac muscle","Bone tissue","Blood vessels","Kidney tubules"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is derived from the endoderm, not the mesoderm. The endoderm gives rise to the epithelium of the digestive tract and associated organs including the pancreas, liver, and thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mesoderm gives rise to multiple tissue types and structures including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - develops from splanchnic mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - arise from angioblasts in the mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKidney tubules\u003C/strong\u003E - develop from intermediate mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - forms from mesenchyme derived from mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mesoderm differentiates into three main regions: paraxial mesoderm (forms somites), intermediate mesoderm (forms urogenital structures), and lateral plate mesoderm (forms body wall, heart, and blood vessels).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mesoderm gives rise to connective tissues, muscles, blood vessels, and organs of the urogenital system.","The mesoderm forms between the ectoderm and endoderm during gastrulation in week 3 of development.","The mesoderm differentiates into paraxial, intermediate, and lateral plate regions."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57049"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15862"}},"stemMedia":{"data":